ngland":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Besford, Worcestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Throckmorton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Throckmorton in Worcestershire, which is named with Old English <i>throc</i> ‘beam bridge’ + <i>mere</i> ‘pool’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","History: The Throckmorton family was powerful and influential in England in Tudor times, but has since almost died out there. American bearers of the name trace their descent from either John Throckmorton (1601–1684) of New England or Robert Throckmorton (1609–1663) of VA."],"variants":[{"name":"Throgmorton","meanings":["English: variant of   Throckmorton  ."]}]},{"name":"Felicia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Felix .  It was popular in Britain in the medieval period (with the vernacular forms  <b>Felice</b> ,  <b>Felis</b> ), but by the 16th century it had become confused with   Phyllis .  In modern times it is in only occasional use."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":39,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":48,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Felicia de Throckmorton was born in 1176, in Throckmorton, Worcestershire, England, her father, John de Throckmorton, was 30 and her mother, Joscelin of Besford, was 31. She married Avice de Derinstone in 1202, in Worcester, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1246, in Warwickshire, England, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1176–1246":"1176–1246","1162–1254":"1162–1254","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1180–1215":"1180–1215","1176–1212":"1176–1212","1212–1260":"1212–1260","1146–1176":"1146–1176","1146–1200":"1146–1200","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1176":"1176","1165":"1165","1162":"1162","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1146":"1146","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","about 1213":"umbes 1213","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","Throckmorton, Worcestershire, England":"Throckmorton, Worcestershire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Besford, Worcestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"1176–1246":"1176–1246","1162–1254":"1162–1254","1165–Male